  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions spans several decades and has evolved significantly:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Emerged as a concept in response to organized crime activities in the early 20th century\n- Initially focused on concealing proceeds from illegal activities like bootlegging and gambling\n\n2. Key Milestone Legislation:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970) - First major US legislation requiring financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Money Laundering Control Act (1986) - Made money laundering a federal criminal offense in the United States\n\n3. International Development:\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established in 1989\n- Developed international standards and recommendations for combating money laundering\n- Promoted global cooperation in tracking and preventing financial crimes\n\n4. Expansion after 9/11:\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001) significantly expanded anti-money laundering (AML) regulations\n- Increased reporting requirements and enhanced international information sharing\n- Connected money laundering more explicitly to terrorism financing\n\n5. Modern Regulatory Framework:\n- Comprehensive international legal frameworks\n- Increased digital transaction tracking\n- Expanding scope to include cryptocurrency and emerging financial technologies\n\nThe legal approach has progressively become more complex and technologically sophisticated over time.",
